metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #211
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”

metadata.name: HOPONO #184
metadata.description:
I’M SORRY / PLEASE FORGIVE ME / THANK YOU / I LOVE YOU
Ho'Oponopono is an ancient Hawaiian spiritual practice that involves learning to heal all things by accepting "Total Responsibility" for everything that surrounds us – confession, repentance, and reconciliation. 
This practice has been part of the French street artist Arthur Simony’s creation for a while, on paper, canvas… and now on the TEZ blockchain!
Original piece by Arthur Simony - October 2022 - Paris, France
Powered by David Ughetto @_dugh x Guillaume Horen @guillaumeh

metadata.name: Natt #7
metadata.description:
Natt is a short exploration of a view. On not so recent travels I captured a photo of a small town across a large body of water. It was night and the photograph was blurry, but the emotion stayed with me. It was an emotion of calm and tranquility, accepting the darkness of night and knowing that across the water was a group of people living together, creating a beacon of light. 

Natt is the generative take on this photograph, attempting to capture the same emotion in a purely digital format. 


Press “space” to pause the animation and “s” to save the current view.

For higher resolutions, add “?pd=x” (x being a number >1) to the url when in live view and refresh, then press “s” to save. Note, for higher values of “x” rendering will take longer, start with a low number like 2-3 and work your way up to the desired size. 


Generative artwork by Tengil, 2022.

For licenses see bundle.js.LICENSE.txt.

metadata.name: Wondering #121
metadata.description:
The work contains a fluid simulation. I put random forces into the simulation and let it run 500 steps to create a flow field and then use it to generate the visuals. 

I choose fluid simulation instead of curl noise or any other noise function because I believe the fluid simulation could generate a movement that's more dynamic and organic. The result is a combination of big and small vortices.


This piece requires WebGL2 to run, please check and make sure this runs on your device in advance. Also you can press the spacebar to toggle the camera control.

metadata.name: Fracture #20
metadata.description:
Fragments of fragments, pieced together.


Please be patient as previews may take a while to generate.
Press 's' in live view to save the current image.
You can modify the URL to specify an image size. Keep in mind that the color palette, styles, and general look of the piece will generally remain the same, but a new image will be created to fit the new dimensions. To do this, add x and y URL parameters to the end of the URL. (Images are created using a pixel ratio of 2, so adding ?x=2560&y1440 to the end of the URL will actually create a 5120x2880 image.)


@teaboswell, 2022
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

For third party license information please see bundle.js.LICENSE.txt

metadata.name: Miniscapes #199
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: NAZCA #116
metadata.description:
Real time animation (WebGL)
Variable dimension
2022

Nazca is a group of living glyphs made in the soil of the GPU. There are 17 figures that get combined and mixed over three layers. The figures vary in complexity but are generally created with vertical and horizontal lines only. Figures have at least one seed, some even have a seed per path. A seed is an oscillating pixel that can be compared to a square wave oscillator of audio synthesis and is usually followed by a path or a set of paths. The purpose of the paths is to send the pixels along the lines to make the figures visible through movement and to create a reduction to pure animation.

👽 Kim Asendorf
